doctus per aliena experimenta parum profici armis si injuriae se- querentur, caussas bellorum statuit excidere. But how was the army to shew upon a. battle-field that it was guiltless of such practices? Perhaps we should understand by ‘caussae’ the pre- texts or suggestions of possible rebellion which the carelessness of the conquerors might give, or which were the effective causes of rebellion. The soldiers were to do their work so thoroughly that there should be no strength left for rebellion.
